{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521962","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521962"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:39:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:39:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13789"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13789"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.01,0.03,0.02,0.71]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6407"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59909"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6407"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13789"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45326"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"2177"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12617"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42933"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44003"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59909"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with pain in his right eye after being hit by a squash ball two hours ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Visual acuity in the right eye is 6/12. Slit lamp examination reveals a 2 mm hyphema in the right eye (Image). The left eye appears normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate surgical evacuation of the hyphema","Topical antibiotics and discharge","Cycloplegic eye drops and oral aspirin","Eye patch and return to normal activities","Eye shield, head elevation, and ophthalmology follow-up"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has sustained a hyphema, which is a collection of blood in the anterior chamber of the eye, typically caused by blunt trauma. The most appropriate initial management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eeye shield, head elevation, and ophthalmology follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach protects the eye from further injury, reduces intraocular pressure, and ensures proper monitoring for potential complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate surgical evacuation\u003C/strong\u003E of the hyphema is not typically necessary for a small (2 mm) hyphema and would be overly aggressive at this stage. Surgery is usually reserved for cases with prolonged poor vision, uncontrolled intraocular pressure, or large hyphemas that don\u0027t resolve with conservative management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical antibiotics and discharge\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate management for a hyphema. While antibiotics may be prescribed to prevent infection, the patient requires closer monitoring and should not be discharged without proper follow-up arrangements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECycloplegic eye drops and oral aspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is an inappropriate treatment. While cycloplegic drops may be used to reduce pain and prevent synechiae formation, aspirin (or any anticoagulant) is contraindicated in hyphema as it increases the risk of rebleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eeye patch and return to normal activities\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient and potentially dangerous. The eye needs protection with a shield rather than a patch, and the patient should be advised to limit activities and keep the head elevated to reduce the risk of rebleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hyphema is a collection of blood in the anterior chamber of the eye, often caused by blunt trauma.","Initial management of hyphema includes eye protection, head elevation, and avoidance of anticoagulants.","Patients with hyphema require close follow-up to monitor for complications such as increased intraocular pressure and rebleeding."],"references":["Woreta FA, Lindsley KB, Gharaibeh A, et al. Medical interventions for traumatic hyphema. Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews 2023, Issue 3. Art. No.: CD005431. DOI: 10.1002/14651858.CD005431.pub5."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45326"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13789"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20730"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20730"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Ik58HLVuNLZW0jJCWCa8ETCnAkgU9J.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Ik58HLVuNLZW0jJCWCa8ETCnAkgU9J.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45326"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-09T16:47:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-09T16:49:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6407"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59909"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[